===Noun===
{{en-noun-reg}}

A "Sunshine Agenda" is a public agenda on which an item for decision has been placed for which the descision making body will not entertain commentary, dicussion or influence during a certain defined time-frame prior to the descision.

Pursuant to given rules, once an item has been placed on a sunshine notice, no
presentations, whether [[wikipedia:Ex_parte|ex parte]] or not, are permitted until one of the following conditions is met:
# the descion making body releases the full text of the order in the proceeding noticed in the Sunshine notice,
# the descion making body deletes the item from the sunshine agenda, or
# the item is returned for further consideration.

Such a prohibition is intended (as in the case of the [[wikipedia:Federal_Communications_Commission|Federal Communications Commission]] [http://www.fcc.gov/]) to give the body "a period of repose" in which to make decisions.  Frequently, an exemption is made from the prohibition of discussion regarding recent actions at widely-attended meetings or symposia.  

Some cynics consider this usage of the "sunshine" term a misnomer as the idea of [[wikipedia:Sunshine_laws|Sunshine Laws]] was to "shed light upon" debate and public policy making.

